{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b220191-4893-44ad-88f6-0ee41f4e35f3","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**Recommended steps:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf issues persist after that, you can also try a clean reinstall:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui --force\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ad307113-7393-4f86-a034-9825dbc085f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a broken .NET MAUI build after an SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me answer directly.","outputTokens":245,"requestId":"0433:1DE8C5:CCA7A9:E73320:6A027961"},"id":"618aa76d-5469-48dc-9aa3-45739b515d56","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:48.538Z","parentId":"8382c4de-ad82-42dc-a9c0-0c9250aaf81d"}
